"# Appendix J — Conway's Game of Life

John Conway wrote down four rules in 1970 and accidentally invented an entire field. The rules:

- A living cell with fewer than 2 living neighbors dies (underpopulation).
- A living cell with 2 or 3 living neighbors survives.
- A living cell with more than 3 living neighbors dies (overpopulation).
- A dead cell with exactly 3 living neighbors becomes alive (reproduction).

That's the whole game. There is no player, no goal, no strategy. You place some cells on a grid, and every generation the whole grid updates according to those rules simultaneously. From those four rules fall out oscillators, gliders, guns, Turing-complete computation, and every philosophical argument about emergence you'll ever hear.

The examples in this appendix run on a small grid — 10 by 10 mostly — because Motoi's default fuel budget favors tight loops. If you want bigger simulations, pass `--fuel 2000000` on the CLI and go to 20×20 or larger. Every example here has been verified against the CLI at the default fuel budget.

## The tick loop

Every example uses the same skeleton: a grid as a Motoi vector of `W*H` cells (each 0 or 1), a `get`/`put!` accessor pair for readability, an `nb-count` that counts the 8 neighbors with wrap-around, and a `step` that reads the old grid and writes a fresh new grid based on the four rules.

The wrap-around is a *toroidal* topology — cells that fall off the right edge come back on the left. It's the simplest boundary condition that has no boundary. Real Conway simulations often use finite grids with dead borders, but wrap-around makes small demos feel bigger.

## J.1 The blinker

The simplest oscillator. Three cells in a row become three cells in a column become three cells in a row, forever. Period 2. Place the blinker horizontally at row 5 and watch it flip vertical on the next generation.

```scheme
(define W 10)
(define H 10)

(define (make-grid) (make-vector (* W H) 0))
(define (idx x y) (+ x (* y W)))
(define (get g x y) (vector-ref g (idx x y)))
(define (put! g x y v) (vector-set! g (idx x y) v))

(define (nb-count g x y)
  (let ((c 0))
    (let dy ((j -1))
      (if (<= j 1)
          (begin
            (let dx ((i -1))
              (if (<= i 1)
                  (begin
                    (if (not (and (= i 0) (= j 0)))
                        (let ((nx (modulo (+ x i) W))
                              (ny (modulo (+ y j) H)))
                          (set! c (+ c (get g nx ny)))))
                    (dx (+ i 1)))))
            (dy (+ j 1)))))
    c))

(define (step g)
  (let ((n (make-grid)))
    (let outer ((y 0))
      (if (< y H)
          (begin
            (let inner ((x 0))
              (if (< x W)
                  (begin
                    (let* ((cur (get g x y))
                           (cnt (nb-count g x y))
                           (alive? (or (and (= cur 1) (or (= cnt 2) (= cnt 3)))
                                       (and (= cur 0) (= cnt 3)))))
                      (put! n x y (if alive? 1 0)))
                    (inner (+ x 1)))))
            (outer (+ y 1)))))
    n))

(define (draw g)
  (clear)
  (begin-frame)
  (set-color 'black)
  (rect-fill 0 0 80 80)
  (set-color 'white)
  (let outer ((y 0))
    (if (< y H)
        (begin
          (let inner ((x 0))
            (if (< x W)
                (begin
                  (if (= 1 (get g x y))
                      (fill-rect (* x 8) (* y 8) 8 8))   ; alias fill-rect
                  (inner (+ x 1)))))
          (outer (+ y 1)))))
  (end-frame)
  (render))

(define g (make-grid))
(put! g 4 5 1)
(put! g 5 5 1)
(put! g 6 5 1)

(draw g)
(set! g (step g))
(draw g)
(set! g (step g))
(draw g)
(display \"conway-1 done: blinker, 2 generations.\")
(newline)
```

**What you see.** Frame 1: three horizontal white cells at row 5. Frame 2: three vertical white cells centered on the same middle cell. Frame 3: back to horizontal. It never stops.

## J.2 The glider

The most famous shape in the game — a five-cell pattern that walks diagonally across the grid, repeating its shape every four generations, one cell down and one cell to the right.

```scheme
(define W 10)
(define H 10)

(define (make-grid) (make-vector (* W H) 0))
(define (idx x y) (+ x (* y W)))
(define (get g x y) (vector-ref g (idx x y)))
(define (put! g x y v) (vector-set! g (idx x y) v))

(define (nb-count g x y)
  (let ((c 0))
    (let dy ((j -1))
      (if (<= j 1)
          (begin
            (let dx ((i -1))
              (if (<= i 1)
                  (begin
                    (if (not (and (= i 0) (= j 0)))
                        (let ((nx (modulo (+ x i) W))
                              (ny (modulo (+ y j) H)))
                          (set! c (+ c (get g nx ny)))))
                    (dx (+ i 1)))))
            (dy (+ j 1)))))
    c))

(define (step g)
  (let ((n (make-grid)))
    (let outer ((y 0))
      (if (< y H)
          (begin
            (let inner ((x 0))
              (if (< x W)
                  (begin
                    (let* ((cur (get g x y))
                           (cnt (nb-count g x y))
                           (alive? (or (and (= cur 1) (or (= cnt 2) (= cnt 3)))
                                       (and (= cur 0) (= cnt 3)))))
                      (put! n x y (if alive? 1 0)))
                    (inner (+ x 1)))))
            (outer (+ y 1)))))
    n))

(define (draw g)
  (clear)
  (begin-frame)
  (set-color 'black)
  (rect-fill 0 0 80 80)
  (set-color 'lime)
  (let outer ((y 0))
    (if (< y H)
        (begin
          (let inner ((x 0))
            (if (< x W)
                (begin
                  (if (= 1 (get g x y))
                      (filled-rectangle (* x 8) (* y 8) 8 8))  ; alias
                  (inner (+ x 1)))))
          (outer (+ y 1)))))
  (end-frame)
  (render))

;; The classic glider:
;;  . X .
;;  . . X
;;  X X X
(define g (make-grid))
(put! g 2 1 1)
(put! g 3 2 1)
(put! g 1 3 1) (put! g 2 3 1) (put! g 3 3 1)

(draw g)
(set! g (step g))
(draw g)
(set! g (step g))
(draw g)
(display \"conway-2 done: glider, 2 generations.\")
(newline)
```

**What you see.** Frame 1: the L-plus-hat shape. Frames 2 and 3: the shape twists into intermediate configurations. If you ran four generations, you'd see the original shape reappear, but shifted one cell down and to the right — one glider-step. On a torus the glider walks forever. Also: two generations at the default fuel budget is the ceiling. Pass `--fuel 2000000` to see more.

## J.3 The beacon oscillator

Two 2×2 blocks touching at a corner. Period 2. Alternates between the two blocks appearing solid and appearing hollow along the diagonal.

```scheme
(define W 10)
(define H 10)

(define (make-grid) (make-vector (* W H) 0))
(define (idx x y) (+ x (* y W)))
(define (get g x y) (vector-ref g (idx x y)))
(define (put! g x y v) (vector-set! g (idx x y) v))

(define (nb-count g x y)
  (let ((c 0))
    (let dy ((j -1))
      (if (<= j 1)
          (begin
            (let dx ((i -1))
              (if (<= i 1)
                  (begin
                    (if (not (and (= i 0) (= j 0)))
                        (let ((nx (modulo (+ x i) W))
                              (ny (modulo (+ y j) H)))
                          (set! c (+ c (get g nx ny)))))
                    (dx (+ i 1)))))
            (dy (+ j 1)))))
    c))

(define (step g)
  (let ((n (make-grid)))
    (let outer ((y 0))
      (if (< y H)
          (begin
            (let inner ((x 0))
              (if (< x W)
                  (begin
                    (let* ((cur (get g x y))
                           (cnt (nb-count g x y))
                           (alive? (or (and (= cur 1) (or (= cnt 2) (= cnt 3)))
                                       (and (= cur 0) (= cnt 3)))))
                      (put! n x y (if alive? 1 0)))
                    (inner (+ x 1)))))
            (outer (+ y 1)))))
    n))

(define (draw g)
  (clear)
  (begin-frame)
  (set-color 'navy)
  (rect-fill 0 0 80 80)
  (set-color 'gold)
  (let outer ((y 0))
    (if (< y H)
        (begin
          (let inner ((x 0))
            (if (< x W)
                (begin
                  (if (= 1 (get g x y))
                      (rect-fill (* x 8) (* y 8) 8 8))
                  (inner (+ x 1)))))
          (outer (+ y 1)))))
  (end-frame)
  (render))

;; Beacon:
;;  X X . .
;;  X X . .
;;  . . X X
;;  . . X X
(define g (make-grid))
(put! g 2 2 1) (put! g 3 2 1)
(put! g 2 3 1) (put! g 3 3 1)
(put! g 4 4 1) (put! g 5 4 1)
(put! g 4 5 1) (put! g 5 5 1)

(draw g)
(set! g (step g))
(draw g)
(display \"conway-3 done: beacon oscillator, 1 step.\")
(newline)
```

**What you see.** Two golden 2×2 blocks touching at the corner on a navy background. After the step, the inner cells of each block have died (each corner cell has three neighbors — no, wait, count again — actually the *corner* cells in the interior have four neighbors, so they die by overpopulation, and the previously-empty gaps between the blocks come alive at count-3). Blink.

## J.4 A random-seed soup

Fill the grid with random cells, then step it once and see what settles. Most cells will die immediately, some will form small stable configurations (still-lifes), some will start oscillating.

```scheme
(define W 10)
(define H 10)

(define (make-grid) (make-vector (* W H) 0))
(define (idx x y) (+ x (* y W)))
(define (get g x y) (vector-ref g (idx x y)))
(define (put! g x y v) (vector-set! g (idx x y) v))

(define (nb-count g x y)
  (let ((c 0))
    (let dy ((j -1))
      (if (<= j 1)
          (begin
            (let dx ((i -1))
              (if (<= i 1)
                  (begin
                    (if (not (and (= i 0) (= j 0)))
                        (let ((nx (modulo (+ x i) W))
                              (ny (modulo (+ y j) H)))
                          (set! c (+ c (get g nx ny)))))
                    (dx (+ i 1)))))
            (dy (+ j 1)))))
    c))

(define (step g)
  (let ((n (make-grid)))
    (let outer ((y 0))
      (if (< y H)
          (begin
            (let inner ((x 0))
              (if (< x W)
                  (begin
                    (let* ((cur (get g x y))
                           (cnt (nb-count g x y))
                           (alive? (or (and (= cur 1) (or (= cnt 2) (= cnt 3)))
                                       (and (= cur 0) (= cnt 3)))))
                      (put! n x y (if alive? 1 0)))
                    (inner (+ x 1)))))
            (outer (+ y 1)))))
    n))

(define (seed-random! g)
  (let outer ((y 0))
    (if (< y H)
        (begin
          (let inner ((x 0))
            (if (< x W)
                (begin
                  (if (> (random) 0.6)
                      (put! g x y 1))
                  (inner (+ x 1)))))
          (outer (+ y 1))))))

(define (draw g)
  (clear)
  (begin-frame)
  (set-color 'black)
  (rect-fill 0 0 80 80)
  (set-color 'orange)
  (let outer ((y 0))
    (if (< y H)
        (begin
          (let inner ((x 0))
            (if (< x W)
                (begin
                  (if (= 1 (get g x y))
                      (put-pixel (* x 8) (* y 8)))     ; alias put-pixel
                  (inner (+ x 1)))))
          (outer (+ y 1)))))
  (end-frame)
  (render))

(define g (make-grid))
(seed-random! g)

(draw g)
(set! g (step g))
(draw g)
(display \"conway-4 done: 10x10 random soup, 1 generation.\")
(newline)
```

**What you see.** The first frame is a random scatter of orange dots — about 40% coverage. The second frame is that same soup after one step. Most of the isolated dots have died. Any 2×2 block has stayed. Any three-in-a-row will have started blinking. Every run looks different because `random` is stochastic; pass `--seed 42` for reproducibility.

## J.5 Two colonies

Place a horizontal blinker in the upper-left and a vertical blinker in the lower-right of a 10×10 grid. On a small torus, the two colonies are near enough to interact via the wrap-around neighborhood. Color them differently based on which half of the board they were born in.

```scheme
(define W 10)
(define H 10)

(define (make-grid) (make-vector (* W H) 0))
(define (idx x y) (+ x (* y W)))
(define (get g x y) (vector-ref g (idx x y)))
(define (put! g x y v) (vector-set! g (idx x y) v))

(define (nb-count g x y)
  (let ((c 0))
    (let dy ((j -1))
      (if (<= j 1)
          (begin
            (let dx ((i -1))
              (if (<= i 1)
                  (begin
                    (if (not (and (= i 0) (= j 0)))
                        (let ((nx (modulo (+ x i) W))
                              (ny (modulo (+ y j) H)))
                          (set! c (+ c (get g nx ny)))))
                    (dx (+ i 1)))))
            (dy (+ j 1)))))
    c))

(define (step g)
  (let ((n (make-grid)))
    (let outer ((y 0))
      (if (< y H)
          (begin
            (let inner ((x 0))
              (if (< x W)
                  (begin
                    (let* ((cur (get g x y))
                           (cnt (nb-count g x y))
                           (alive? (or (and (= cur 1) (or (= cnt 2) (= cnt 3)))
                                       (and (= cur 0) (= cnt 3)))))
                      (put! n x y (if alive? 1 0)))
                    (inner (+ x 1)))))
            (outer (+ y 1)))))
    n))

(define (draw g)
  (clear)
  (begin-frame)
  (set-color 'black)
  (rect-fill 0 0 80 80)
  (let outer ((y 0))
    (if (< y H)
        (begin
          (let inner ((x 0))
            (if (< x W)
                (begin
                  (if (= 1 (get g x y))
                      (begin
                        (set-color (if (< x 5) 'crimson 'skyblue))
                        (fill-rect (* x 8) (* y 8) 8 8)))  ; alias fill-rect
                  (inner (+ x 1)))))
          (outer (+ y 1)))))
  (end-frame)
  (render))

(define g (make-grid))
(put! g 1 1 1)
(put! g 2 1 1)
(put! g 3 1 1)
(put! g 8 7 1)
(put! g 8 8 1)
(put! g 8 9 1)

(draw g)
(set! g (step g))
(draw g)
(display \"conway-5 done: two colonies, 1 step (each a blinker).\")
(newline)
```

**What you see.** Frame 1: a crimson three-in-a-row in the upper-left, a sky-blue three-in-a-column in the lower-right. Frame 2: the crimson blinker has rotated to vertical, the sky-blue blinker has rotated to horizontal. The two-color coloring is a lie the drawing tells us — Conway's Game doesn't know about colors, only cells — but it lets you see the two lineages.

## Why the Game of Life matters

Conway's Game is *Turing complete*. You can build a working computer inside it. There are patterns that simulate arbitrary computation, patterns that build copies of themselves, patterns that grow forever without repeating.

None of that was designed. It was *discovered*. Four rules on a grid gave rise to a universe that turned out to contain arbitrary computation. That's the reason mathematicians and computer scientists have been staring at Life for fifty years: it's the smallest theorem-generating machine anyone has ever found.

If you want to keep going, look up: the R-pentomino (five cells that stabilize after 1103 generations), Gosper's glider gun (13 cells that emit a glider every 30 steps forever), the highlife variant (born on 3 *or* 6). Every one of these fits inside the same four-line rule and the same tick loop you just wrote.
